{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"87110c6d-851a-4b7b-b63e-a6f82524243f","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes** (everything after `--` is passed to the new platform):\n\n| VSTest flag | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n`--filter` stays before `--` — the SDK translates it for you.\n\n**Required NuGet packages** in your test project:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a18cce4c-19db-481d-a6f7-e4ca38c4887f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling changes, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `dotnet test` still works but the underlying runner changes\n- Filter syntax changes from `--filter` to `--filter` (same) or `--treenode-filter`\n- Logger changes: `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- Code coverage: `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` → `--coverage` (with Microsoft.CodeCoverage)\n\n\n- Blame options shift: `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`, `--blame-hang` becomes `--hangdump`, and `--blame-hang-timeout` becomes `--hangdump-timeout`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can run the test executable directly or continue using `dotnet test`, though the argument syntax changes. When using `dotnet test` with Microsoft.Testing.Platform projects, newer SDK versions handle the argument passing automatically, so I need to show you the correct mapping for your specific command.\n\nFor the old command with filters, logging, code coverage, and blame options, the new equivalents are: the filter argument stays the same when passed through `dotnet test`, the logger becomes a trx report flag, code coverage collection maps to coverage flags with the cobertura format, and the crash/hang blame options convert to their dump equivalents with the timeout parameter adjusted accordingly.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the cleanest approach is using the `--` separator to pass arguments directly to the test runner, which gives you explicit control over the translation. You can also run the test executable directly if you need even more precision. Completing the filter syntax and mapping the key arguments between the two test runners. The `--filter` option before the `--` separator stays with `dotnet test` for compatibility, while arguments after `--` go directly to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, where `--report-trx` replaces the logger configuration and the coverage and dump options carry through as-is.\n\nEach of these features requires its own NuGet extension package to function properly.","outputTokens":1652,"requestId":"E83F:1F9B94:264F7D7:28CB1E3:6A049406"},"id":"0be10f48-e749-4ff0-926e-454ee7b38cfa","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:09:21.309Z","parentId":"fc0c924c-6a8b-4c4a-89f1-3ae4360c75f9"}
